          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
      ECOWAS leadership shift
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/west-africa-organized-crime-political-instability-bio-ecowas-leadership.jpg" alt="Organized crime is on the rise in West Africa amid political and economic instability, which Bio has to address during his period" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          Organized crime is on the rise in West Africa amid political and economic instability, which Bio has to address during his period. Credits: President Tinubu’s official X handle</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       Sierra Leone’s President, Julius Maada Bio, is assuming the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-spotlight-h1-1-leadership-of-ecowas" target="_blank">leadership of ECOWAS</a> during a challenging time. During his speech, Bio pledged to prioritize democracy, regional security, economic integration, and institutional reform. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
     His predecessor, Nigeria’s Bola Tinubu, leaves behind a fractured region. There were military coups in Burkina Faso, Mali, and Niger. Subsequently, these <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-spotlight-h1-2-countries-left-ecowas" target="_blank">countries left ECOWAS</a>, citing ideological differences, and formed their group, the Alliance of Sahel States (AES). This split hinders ECOWAS’s ability to tackle threats such as terrorism and organized crime. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       The long-planned collective <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-spotlight-h1-3-standby-force" target="_blank">Standby Force</a> remains underfunded and inactive despite $128M EU injection. Meanwhile, popular sentiment in countries like Togo shows growing support for AES over ECOWAS, viewed as bureaucratic and ineffective.</p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       However, analysts warn that while AES presents itself as assertive, it is unstable. They suggest that ECOWAS must evolve or risk irrelevance. Bio’s leadership will be tested by his ability to restore unity and relevance in a divided West Africa. The agreement between ECOWAS and the Sahel junta to fight terrorism is a step in the right direction. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
