     Kazakhstan’s nuclear balance 
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
        Summary: Russia and China will construct Kazakhstan’s nuclear power plants.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Kazakhstan has picked Russia's Rosatom to build its first nuclear power plant, deepening ties with Moscow despite regional shifts. The country may also consider a Chinese firm for a second project. This reflects <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-analysis-h1-7-kazakhstan-s-plan-to-balance" target="_blank">Kazakhstan's plan to balance</a> between the two major powers. Rosatom agreement includes favorable funding, waste disposal, and strong technical capabilities, making it an appealing choice. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          While Astana insists the plant will be state-owned and the decision was apolitical, critics point to Rosatom’s growing regional role and geopolitical motivations. The project, estimated to be $15B and expected to be completed by 2036, will be located near Lake Balkhash. A 2023 referendum saw 71% of voters support the idea of building a nuclear plant to address growing energy deficits. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Ultimately, both projects present significant monetary, environmental, and political challenges. Details of the China agreement are still unclear, and critics raise concerns about transparency in the bidding process. Kazakhstan's nuclear plans reflect a broader goal of navigating relationships with powerful neighbors while preserving its own sovereignty.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
