      <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/strategic-global-alignments-flags-map-us-china-russia-africa-asia.jpg" alt="Global map showing diplomatic or strategic linkages among the U.S., Russia, China, Iran, and various African and Asian nations" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
      <mj-spacer height="10px"/>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-top:4px;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>🇨🇳 China - Historical disagreement.</strong> 
           Tensions between China and Taiwan have escalated into a war of words. China insists Taiwan is part of its territory, citing World War II agreements, and rejects any notion of invasion. Taiwan's President Lai Ching-te asserts the island is an independent nation, with its future to be decided democratically by its people, not by Beijing (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-worldwide-8-war-of-words" target="_blank">war of words</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>🇮🇷 Iran - Nuclear oversight.</strong> 
           US intelligence assessment suggests Trump's assertion that Iran’s nuclear sites were "obliterated" may be overstated. The Defense Intelligence Agency found that Iran’s nuclear program could resume within months and that key materials were moved before the strikes. The Fordow site, buried deep underground, likely survived. Trump and the White House dispute the report's conclusions (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-worldwide-9-nuclear-oversights" target="_blank">nuclear oversights</a>). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>🇪🇹 Ethiopia - Opens border with Eritrea.</strong> 
           After five years of separation due to war and closed borders, Ethiopian and Eritrean border communities reunited in Zalambessa, marking a powerful moment of reconciliation. Families embraced as Eritrean and Tigrayan flags waved side by side. The gathering revived cross-border trade and renewed hope for lasting peace. (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-worldwide-10-neighborly-love" target="_blank">neighborly love</a>). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
          <strong>🇬🇪 Georgia - Politicians jailed.</strong> 
          Four Georgian opposition leaders were jailed for seven to eight months for refusing to testify before a commission set up by the ruling Georgian Dream party. The EU’s Kaja Kallas called the sentences “not proportional” and part of a “repression machine.” The convicted leaders also face two-year bans from public office, and more opposition figures may face similar penalties (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-worldwide-11-democratic-backsliding" target="_blank">democratic backsliding</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
          <strong>🇻🇳 Vietnam - Curbs the death penalty.</strong> 
          Vietnam will abolish the death penalty for eight crimes, including embezzlement and attempts to overthrow the government. The change spares tycoon Truong My Lan, sentenced to death for a $12B fraud, whose punishment will be reduced to imprisonment. Ten crimes, including murder and drug trafficking, will still carry the death penalty (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-worldwide-12-crime-and-punishment" target="_blank">crime and punishment</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
          <strong>🇲🇱 Mali - Agreement with Russia.</strong> 
          Mali and Russia signed agreements to enhance trade and cooperation, including in the nuclear energy sector. During Col Assimi Goïta’s visit to Moscow, President Putin discussed expanding ties in energy, logistics, and security. Military cooperation remains key, despite Wagner’s exit (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-worldwide-13-russia-mali-cooperation" target="_blank">Russia-Mali cooperation</a>).
          </p>
        </mj-text>
