          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
     How did Indians end up in Uganda? 
 
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/indians-in-uganda-merchant-class-retail-textile-construction-history.jpg" alt=" Indians evolved into a merchant and middle class, running retail shops, textile businesses, and construction companies" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>Indians evolved into a merchant and middle class, running retail shops, textile businesses, and construction companies. Credits: Hulton Archive / Getty Images</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Zohran Mamdani’s New York mayoral primary triumph brought Uganda to the map.   Mamdani, who is of Indian origin, was <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-foundation-h1-14-born-in-uganda" target="_blank">born in Uganda</a> but immigrated to the US as a child. Indians came to Uganda primarily during the late 19th and early 20th centuries, driven by British colonial expansion and economic possibility.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         When the British Empire began constructing the Uganda Railway, it recruited around 32,000 Indian laborers, mostly from the Punjab and Gujarat regions. While most laborers returned to India after the railway was completed, about 7,000 chose to stay. Over time, Indian migrants transitioned into roles as traders, shopkeepers, clerks, and civil servants, forming a critical economic middle class. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Through family migration and business networks, the Indian community in Uganda experienced significant growth in the early to mid-20th century. They controlled much of the retail trade and small industry by the 1960s. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        In 1972, President Idi Amin <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-jun-25-foundation-h1-15-expelled-about-70-000-asians" target="_blank">expelled about 70,000 Asians</a>, accusing them of economic sabotage and being disloyal to Uganda. Most expelled Indians resettled in the UK, Canada, and India. Some have since returned to Uganda after the 1990s, when the government encouraged the reconciliation of the diaspora.</p>
        </mj-text>
